(23, 1, '2015-08-22 17:59:42', '2015-08-22 16:59:42', 'Our third interview comes from none other then the very talented and incredible music seeker, Lvlsr Vryhi. The man puts in a ton of work not only in terms of putting together videos, but searching out some of the best music from around the world and Classical Trax couldn’t think of a better person to talk to for our third session of Q&A’s.Check him out \r\n\r\nphoto credit to David Brimacombe\r\n<a href="http://37.60.225.213/~class690/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/lvlsrvryhiBlogPostEg.jpg"><img src="http://37.60.225.213/~class690/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/lvlsrvryhiBlogPostEg-300x300.jpg" alt="lvlsrvryhiBlogPostEg" width="300" height="300" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-22" /></a>\r\n\r\ninterview by Juliette Boos of Handle The Sound\r\n\r\nhttp://handlethesound.tumblr.com/\r\n\r\nJ : Hi ! You’re alright ?\r\n\r\nL : Hullo - I’m fine, but had a fancy ready meal and then ruined it by eating a pot noodle so maybe a little annoyed with myself\r\n\r\nJ: hahaha Could you tell me a bit more about « The Levels Are Very High » ?\r\n\r\nL : It’s predominantly a youtube channel (for rips, premieres and full videos that I make) and a mix series really - I’m interested in being able to give people (producers, DJs etc.) a platform (I guess in a similar way that Matt sees Classical Trax). It’s my way of getting involved but I see it more to do with ‘the scene’ than it is about me\r\n\r\nJ : yeah that’s an alternative to own a label or something i guess\r\n\r\nit’s very nice though\r\n\r\nwhen about did you launched it?\r\n\r\nL: Haha thanks. I’ve always seen it as a bit cobbled together to be honest. \r\nAccording to youtube I started it in January of last year, but that was back when I was just ripping tracks.\r\n\r\nI don’t think I did anything for the first birthday hahah\r\n\r\nIt’s definitely been long enough that I can’t really remember what free time is like - between this and university work I don’t really get a lot of it (my gf’s nodding her head in the corner right now haha)\r\n\r\nJ : hahaha what are you studying at uni?\r\n\r\nyeah i know the feeling\r\n\r\nL : Art History\r\nI’m on the last stretch of my MA at the moment, finishing that in September (no summer for me)\r\n\r\nJ : awww i’m sure you’ll be great\r\n\r\ndo you also dj / produce besides all of this?\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nL : I DJ in so much as I can mix and have drunkenly soundtracked a few parties. But I like doing guestmixes and it’s definitely something I want to focus on more when I’ve got the time. Right now though I’m definitely the guy looking in. \r\nI think my next few things are my Brunswick Sound mix and Matt is getting me to do half of a Radar show in September; that should be fun.\r\nRE: producing - I’ve got a maschine somewhere but any time I touch it I can’t even settle on a kick pattern.\r\n\r\nimage\r\nJ : ohhh i didnt really knew about you being a dj\r\n\r\ni have to admit that i’ve been sleeping on a lot of things recently\r\n\r\nL : I’m stuck with an unreadable DJ name - lvlsrvryhi doesn’t translate very well.\r\nSleeping on things is a major worry of mine. Sometimes I’ll have a heavy weekend and be away from soundcloud and facebook for a couple of days and feel like the entire world has changed since I’ve been gone.\r\n\r\nJ : hahaha me too\r\n\r\nIts seems like you’re digging a lot on the internet to find talented producers that are not known enough. Do you think you could be a stepping-stone for those people ?\r\n\r\nL : Actually, the other week WGWN - who was the first DJ to approach me wanting to do a mix - came down to Brighton for a night out and I think he pretty much said that (me being a stepping-stone etc.) himself. He was very far gone at the time though so maybe it was all fake haha.\r\nA lot of times, especially lately, I’ve asked people for mixes because, with there being so many aspects and points of reference for club and dance music culture now, the best way for me to shed some light on what’s going on is for the producers/DJs involved to filter it themselves.\r\n\r\nJ : yeah that’s true\r\n\r\nwhat artists do you think need more hightlight then?\r\n\r\nL : Hahah. Guess I’ve got to pick out my favourites then. I’m not going to try and list off everyone I think deserves more hype because I’d just forget people or I’d mention someone and then tomorrow they’re picked up by one of the figureheads of a particular scene and I look like a bit of a fool.\r\nI’ve always been happy to use my channel/blog as if its literally me (with a logo standing in for my face I guess), so it’s approachable. I think that’s working, producers send me stuff all the time that I probably would’ve missed otherwise\r\nReally I think everyone should just listen to radio anyway so I’m gonna list off a bunch of shows I try and tune in to every week or month or whatever:\r\n187, Mungo, SagePay, Riz La Teef, Akito, Crazylegs and Handsome Boys on Radar\r\nTrax Couture, Circadian Rhythms, Precious Metals, Slimzee and Roll Through on NTS\r\nBoxed and Celestial Trax on Rinse\r\nand anytime anyone from Staycore or NAAFI is on deck as well.\r\n\r\nJ : yeah it’s hard to name them all\r\n\r\nhaha\r\n\r\ndoes sometimes producers ask you to release like an EP on lvlsr?\r\n\r\nL : No one has come to me with anything more than a track so far\r\nI focus on trying to give back to anyone who gives to me, which is why I started making videos to go with tracks people wanted me to put up. Even if it’s a simpler thing I want to be involved and not benefiting from someone’s track without doing much myself\r\nIf I ever was going to put up much more than one tune from someone I’d probably end up trying to do a video for each track and not go outside for a full week haha.\r\n\r\nJ : haha yeah i see\r\n\r\nbut do you think, in the future, you could become a label? and keeping making videos? or you prefer to keep it that way\r\n\r\nL : I’m not much of a future planner. I’ve got this .txt file that’s labelled “Schedule” in all caps and I don’t think I’ve opened it in about two weeks. I don’t think I’ll be turning into a label any time soon - I wouldn’t mind working on a compilation or something similar but I doubt it would be a regular thing.\r\nMe, Grime Disciple, Future Curse and Classical Trax may be developing a joint venture in the future. Though I’m also really disorganized so I might weigh everyone down haha.\r\n\r\nJ : yeah you’re doing it the right way\r\n\r\ntake your time\r\n\r\neverything doesnt have to end up as a label\r\n\r\nWhat’s your vision about the actual club scene ?\r\n\r\nL : Sometimes I’m pretty unsure what I mean when I talk about a ''scene’ to anyone. Most of my experience with it is massively virtual and definitely a product of being in a community like Classical Trax and knowing a bunch of London DJs. I think people can get a little too caught up in approaching club cultures as if they all habit the same space on the internet instead of properly taking in what’s around them, I’m 100% guilty of that myself. \r\nIt’s great that collectives and aesthetics can exist without borders to some extent but it obviously leads to misrepresentation and co-option as easily as it does new relationships and a broadening of club culture as a whole.\r\nI’ve started tweeting at or messaging people when I like a tune of theirs because I think if you don’t engage with a producer you can basically consume their music and play it out yourself without their knowledge; then you just miss out on communicating with them and can’t reach more of an understanding behind what’s specific about what they’re doing.\r\n\r\nJ : do you think people don’t talk enough to producers and all?\r\n\r\nL : Most people are a bit faceless on the internet so it can be difficult to see why you would try and interact with them. And yeah I wouldn’t expect every producer or DJ to respond to me just like I don’t get back to everyone who sends me a message, but I think the intention says a lot. Like, whether it’s just because I’m a bit drunk or whatever, I always try and say to a DJ if I think it was a good set if I see them out and it probably comes across really moist but they just got me to dance for an hour straight so I’ve already embarrassed myself plenty.\r\n\r\nJ : awww yes\r\n\r\ndo you go out a lot in brighton?\r\n\r\nhow’s the music scene over there?\r\n\r\nL : A lot of new promoters have just come up, though most of them for House and Techno (Wave Function being an exception - they had a Wisdom Teeth night on last month) but there’s a massive lack of clubs for them - new venues are cropping up here and there but it’s definitely smaller than when I started uni like three and a half years ago. Really though the saviour of the scene are the Mute guys who’ve been around for a year or so now. They put on the nights I look forward to (besides one-offs) both in Brighton and in London and are kind of on their own thing bookings wise. One of the best things about living here though is being able to go up to London for a night out without much hassle - so I definitely get to experience music on a system and in a club regularly enough, money willing.\r\n\r\nJ : Nice so much things i didnt.know\r\n\r\nDoes the music scene in Brighton has influenced you in your tastes in matters of music ?\r\n\r\nL : I’d probably say no to be honest - I’ve always come at it looking for what I wanted to hear out rather than going on a whim. That’s probably a product of growing up and hearing and liking most of the UK-based club sounds before moving down here though. \r\nBecky (aka LVLSRVRY_GF): ''Stephen picks the nights out for our group of friends. Personally, I didn’t connect with club music that much before moving down to Brighton, but getting exposed to  the stuff that he’s playing in his room (or my room) in a club environment has given it another dimension (especially communally). I’ve learnt what I do like and what I don’t like a lot more - not that that stops him from playing whatever he wants’\r\n\r\nJ : How do you proceed to make your videos ?\r\n\r\nL : I’ll listen to the tune a bunch of times and then just spend a day or so looking for sources that fit the mood of the tune (or just random stuff I think looks interesting). I’ve gotten in the habit of mapping out the patterns of each element in the tune and then messing with them to make them fit. A lot of times it can be a bit arduous and super time consuming, but I’m pretty happy with how most of the videos have come out. \r\nI used to bully windows movie maker into working for me, most of the early videos were with that and the quality fluctuated depending on how many times WMM crashed. Now I’m using premiere though and it’s more my computer freaking out than the program. I don’t think I’m really very good or experienced with it yet despite how many hours I’ve sunk in, but I’m pretty content with letting the tracks dictate the video rather than me.\r\n\r\nJ : Yeah i think you are doing a very great job smile emoticon\r\n\r\nThe interview is almost finished\r\n\r\nI just got one more thing\r\n\r\nIt’s like an open question You say such interesting things so if there is any artist you like atm or city you wanna visit things you wanna experiment or type of music you think deserve more fame or anything really just tell me\r\n\r\nL : I’ve kind of thought of moving around and leaving the UK a fair amount and I would like to travel more, especially to visit the US since the last time I went I was more interested in the different flavours of cheetos and that cartoon network had ''rude stuff’ on after a certain time at night than club music (I was like 11). But I don’t think I’d ever really want to live anywhere else, I’m too entrenched here and I’d just get more annoyed with all the nights I was missing by not being near London (even though I miss loads now anyway).\r\n\r\nMost of the cities I’d want to go out to and experience things first hand are tied, for me at least, to particular labels/parties and what they’re doing there: Mexico City (for NAAFI), Lisbon (for Principe), Paris (for Sound Pellegrino) and Grenoble (for Narco Polo), Brooklyn (for Purple Tape Pedigree / AdHoc and DWMS), Kosovo (for Angry Youth), Milan (for Stream). There’s a bunch more obviously and I’m getting ahead of myself since I don’t have any money anyway haha.\r\n\r\nReally though, since I finish uni in September, I’m basically going to continue doing the same stuff I’ve been doing but step it up. And devote the time I was spending on university work on mixing so I can step onto my mate’s radio shows and ruin them all. As for an artist (if i had to pick one), and it might just be because he’s playing on Roll Through on NTS tonight, but ETEVLEH does not get enough attention. He sent me an EP a little while back that is a pretty original take on Grime, but no one has picked it up yet. He also seems to bring to it a lot of the same influences (musical and otherwise) that I’ve always been caught up in visually so I guess that’s another reason why I get a lot from his music.\r\n\r\nJ : Okay thank you very much !\r\n\r\nCheck him out !!!!!\r\n\r\nhttp://lvlsrvryhigh.tumblr.com/\r\n\r\nhttps://twitter.com/LVLSRVRYHI\r\n\r\nhttps://soundcloud.com/thelevelsareveryhigh\r\n\r\nhttps://www.facebook.com/TheLevelsAreVeryHigh\r\n\r\nhttps://www.youtube.com/user/thelevelsareveryhigh\r\n', 'CT Q&A #003- The Levels Are Very High', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-08-22 17:59:42', '2015-08-22 16:59:42', '', 1, 'http://37.60.225.213/~class690/2015/08/22/1-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
