(56, 1, '2015-09-02 20:39:22', '2015-09-02 19:39:22', '<strong>You’re a purveyor of many things…DJing/producing/radio show hosting &amp; designing (for Purple Tape Pedigree’s clothing range). When was it that you realised you had an interest in all these areas? </strong>\r\n\r\nI caught the music bug real young! By first grade, I was sneaking rap music videos after school (shout out Video Music Box) and had my walkman radio tuned to KISS FM on Saturday nights with the volume super low so my pops wouldn’t hear whatever Mr. Magic was playing. When I was 13-14 years old, I knew I had to get into it and I always thought the DJ was the cool guy. I fucked around with making pause tapes and writing little bullshit raps in class…but it wasn’t until I hit freshman year of high school - I saved up enough for turntables and got some belt-driven Gemini’s. I taught myself how to mix and scratch on those dainty things - spent DAYS in my room working on mixes. The routine then was, every Friday, myself and a few friends worked on a mixtape for that week, wrote/recorded freestyle rap intros, slept, then woke up and went shopping for new releases/bootlegs/promos/white labels, then came back and repeated until it was Monday, again.\r\n\r\nI went through phases with it. One point I was a full-on DJ. Then I wanted to rap which led me to get my first “sampler” (Roland JS-30…jeez) and figure out how to make beats. Then I saved enough and bought 1200’s and got pretty decent at being a technical DJ. I quit halfway through college, wanting to just rap and produce. I ended up doing a few shows as a rapper, actually, my first and only solo show was in the basement of CBGB’s at this party my guys Bricks Avalon and HCR (now Ron Morelli, of L.I.E.S.) used to throw as VF Productions. Still have that footage somewhere.\r\n\r\nIn 2004, I ended up getting some beats over to the Diplomats and actually got two tracks placed. That was an experience - kind of left me not wanting to ever have to rely on someone else (i.e. a manager), so since then, I’ve toyed with two different “indie/D.I.Y.” imprints: Sonic Drunk (2005-2008) and Purple Tape Pedigree (2009-forever).\r\n\r\nThe clothes came about because I’ve always wanted to customize my gear and I was once in a hardcore band (I guess) - a stint during which yielded a fairly larger amount of merch than finished music. That’s what got me into dealing with screen-printed graphic tees as a medium.\r\n\r\n<strong>Growing up, who/what were your biggest inspirations when it came to envisaging a career in music and fashion?</strong>\r\n\r\nBiggest inspirations: RZA, Tricky, Tom Waits, Rodney Mullen, Peter Gabriel, army suits, Blade Runner, Bjork, Roc Raida, Stretch &amp; Bobbito, Bill Murray, being a teen in 90’s New York City.\r\n\r\n<strong>Talk me through how you and Note (your right-hand in PTP &amp; co-host of the now-defunct Fresh Out the Box) came to meet?</strong>\r\n\r\nHaaaa! Real shit, we first connected on an Internet forum called Superfuture, back in 2007/2008. There was a small group of heads who would exchange posts about rap, hardcore punk/metal, old cyberpunk computer games, anime, etc. - rather than “What Are You Wearing Today?” You could also always sniff out another New Yorker on the message boards, so we had a few friendly exchanges. One day he ran up on me in Soho like, “Yo! What’s good man?” I guess he recognized me from my Myspace profile I had linked a few times? Shit was pretty automatic since then and after about a year of me running the old Purple Tape Pedigree blog, I felt like I could use another hand. I trusted him fully and he was down to work. Note’s a very rare breed of friend to find: 1000% loyalty and wit.\r\n\r\n<strong>…This is a bit of a random question but what was it that inspired the name for PTP?</strong>\r\n\r\n“Purple Tape” is a reference to the Raekwon album, Only Built 4 Cuban Linx. People started calling it the “purple tape” because it came out as a purple cassette - really rare that a tape would be a colour other than clear or black back then. That’s a hustler’s move to separate his/her product from the rest. To this day, the purple tape is one of our favorite albums of all-time. PTP basically means “striving for perfection.”\r\n\r\n<strong>You established PTP in 2009 and when you look back on your collective’s existence up to now, what are the moments that stand out in your mind as ones you’re really proud of?</strong>\r\n\r\nThe numerous “family-style” meals we’ve had and how the table has grown over the years, hahaha. The really solid handshakes and numerous late nights we’ve shared.\r\n\r\n<strong>You’re a native New Yorker and chose to stay in your hometown for your career…what is it about the city that you really like? Was there ever a point when you considered relocating somewhere else to pursue your interests?</strong>\r\n\r\nI feel like my career is still “just beginning,” you know? In the way that I haven’t yet felt that “grand statement making moment” occur.\r\n\r\nAs much as New York has changed, for better or for worse, it’s still a rather electric place. I’m kind of addicted to the chaotic pacing of it all. Lately, I’ve been trying to clock the way my mind works, in terms of how I manage to remind myself of 3rd-tier tasks for the day, those which I forgot to jot down earlier. There’s a lot to experience and so much diversity, still.\r\n\r\nYes, I’ve definitely considered moving elsewhere to change things up - perhaps to make it all feel super new and lower the risk of a heart attack (or just so I can have that much of an edge up on everyone else who are moving at 1/10th the speed). Sometimes, it’s like, “fuck it, I''ma move to Portland, Maine, and create in some little bubble.” But I think a move for me would be best as a giant leap to a new, bustling country and currency: somewhere in Asia.\r\n\r\n<strong>For someone who’s never visited New York (or even the States for that matter), what nights/shops/restaurants/bars etc, would you recommend if you were to be my ‘city guide’ as it were?</strong>\r\n\r\nI AM THE CITY GUIDE. ASK ABOUT ME.\r\n\r\nBut really, like I kinda said, there’s a lot I’m still finding as new, experience-wise, in this city. I’d definitely say the museums (American Museum of Natural History, especially), downtown (Soho and East Village) for shopping and food, Chinatown Fair arcade and Mei Li Wah’s baked roast pork buns and mad food in Chinatown, Joe’s for a certified plain slice of NYC pizza, Sunny &amp; Annie’s for the best sandwiches you can get 24 hours a day, H&amp;H for the best “everything bagel” you can get 24 hours a day, 2nd Ave Deli for pastrami/corned beef/brisket on rye, uptown 119th or Dyckman for the haze/piff, Astoria (Queens) for B.Z. Grill and more food, Brooklyn to hit Palisades for a proper D.I.Y. venue that is up for anything.\r\n\r\nAs far as nights, it ranges. So much goes on, every week…but also venues change for the various parties so it’s hard to really subscribe to many of them. That’s why I choose to stay at Palisades for the DWMS series PTP puts on - if it ain’t broke…\r\n\r\nBut massive love to Mixpak, Reconstrvct, and AdHoc: some of the most consistent night-makers, for many years now.\r\n\r\n<strong>I hear you’re coming over to London in November…what have you got planned?</strong>\r\n\r\nYeaaaa…gonna be the first time across the Atlantic! I’ll be playing a bunch of things it looks like: nights as well as radio. Shouts to everyone trying to lock it down, but can’t announce anything quite yet - it’s gonna be a full 2-weeks. Wanna definitely say “hi” to my HER Records fam, Trax Couture, Local Action, Coyote, Liminal Sounds, Crazylegs, Gang Fatale, Dark0, Wen, Tropical Waste, Bala Club, and plenty more.\r\n\r\nAlso, looking to get out to Dublin and play a night with Glacial Sound and co.\r\n\r\nLooking to hang with as many of the British crew as possible. There’s gonna be 4-6 of us PTP heads out there. Gonna eat lots of curry and recreate Animal House via someone’s Air BNB\r\n\r\n<strong>Finally…what have you and Note got planned for PTP for the remainder of the year and into 2016? Are there any other areas you guys would like to branch out into?</strong>\r\n\r\nI’ve got a pretty tight/hefty release schedule planned for September through the first quarter of 2016. The plan this year was to fully establish PTP as a record label (beyond other things). It’s looking VERY clear that this is about to happen in a really lovely way. Putting out some split 12"s with talent from HER Rex, Gang Fatale, NAAFI, Keysound, and some surprises. Also, releasing Joey Labeija’s Shattered Dreams album (limited release on vinyl), an EP by DJ New Jersey Drone, and some other things I’ll keep on the low for a bit more. Expect a video or two, as well!\r\n\r\nDWMS10 is October 10th - the last one of the year. I’ll also be playing a few shows as well as finishing up some more mixes, continuing our monthly PTP x Radar Radio show, and working on more of my own music.\r\n\r\nNote will be doing visuals for DWMS10 (as has been the case since the beginning), and I know he is working on some other graphical/motion-active things. Shit, he’s probably gonna take some of that to London and put on a show for ya’ll. Note’s the guy who will pop up with another crazy shirt or two tomorrow - always got something in the works. Everyone in the crew is a workhorse on his/her own. They inspire and push me to do more, all the time. I really love them.\r\n\r\nout to Geng and the entire PTP squad\r\n\r\nhttps://soundcloud.com/purpletapepedigree\r\n\r\nhttp://www.twitter.com/purpicide', 'CT Q&A #004-Geng of PTP', 'Our fourth interview in our Q&A series comes from one of my favorite curators, deejays and just a all around honest and great person, Geng. Check out the amazing interview.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'ct-qa-004-geng-of-ptp', '', '', '2015-09-02 21:29:09', '2015-09-02 20:29:09', '', 0, 'http://37.60.225.213/~class690/?p=56', 0, 'post', '', 0),
