(88, 1, '2015-09-22 18:32:37', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '<a href="http://37.60.225.213/~class690/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/6Nuv4fP.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-89" src="http://37.60.225.213/~class690/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/6Nuv4fP-300x150.png" alt="6Nuv4fP" width="300" height="150" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>Kush Jones</b> is a NYC native who has been grinding out his own corner in the underground dance music scene with an eclectic mixture of sounds and styles; from Jersey Club to Juke, that are evident not just in his work as a DJ but also as a producer. Having gained attention from electronic music powerhouse The Nest and joining the artist roster over at Trill.Wav, we took a moment to sit down and ask him where he’s been, where he’s going and anything else we could fit between.\r\n\r\ninterview by JG JOUR\r\n\r\nClassical Trax:\r\nWe’ll start off by getting you to tell us a bit about yourself, tell the people who you are, what you do and what a day in the life is for Kush Jones?\r\n\r\n<b>Kush Jones:</b>\r\nMy real name is Aaron, I am a New York City native. My favorite sounds are disco and old house records. The first piece of music I ever brought was Jay-Z’s Reasonable Doubt album. I make music occasionally but love playing out other people’s stuff. Still trying to figure out what I want to sound like which is awesome because it confuses people and prevents them from labeling me.\r\n\r\nClassical Trax:\r\nThat’s a strong first purchase. You said that you try to prevent being labeled but if you had to describe your sound to people using, for example, only the title of any book, film or game; what would you choose?\r\n\r\n<b>Kush Jones:</b>\r\nThat’s tough, I can’t put one title down on it. If it means anything my favorite game is Metal Gear Solid, I really enjoyed the first Jurassic Park movie and I don’t read books too much, just articles.\r\n\r\nClassical Trax:\r\nI’d say Metal Gear Solid is a good answer man; you said you like to confuse and prevent people from labeling you &amp; that game is definitely confusing. So how did you get into music originally? Was this always where you wanted to take things?\r\n\r\n<b>Kush Jones:</b>\r\nI originally made music in high school for a class and it was when I got my first copy of a DAW (Reason) to produce on. From there I made songs and I got interested in learning how to mix so I started working on DJing, almost a 7-year process.\r\n\r\nClassical Trax:\r\nThat’s quite a different journey from the “clubber to DJ to producer” classic. Do you think it’s helped you to stand out as DJ?\r\n\r\n<b>Kush Jones:</b>\r\nI’d say as far as my mixing technique, isn’t anything too varying as I am still learning. When it comes to selection, I think what I play stands out for the fact that it’s music people love but wouldn’t “conventionally” go together. I still think people should blend good jersey club with good techno. That’s only my opinion though.\r\n\r\nClassical Trax:\r\nI could not agree with that more! It’s great to see more DJs flexing a larger variety of records and combining newer sounds with things people have references for. Definitely one way to get people to better understand where a lot of more club focused sounds come from. Who would you say has influenced you most both in your DJing and Production respectively?\r\n\r\n<b>Kush Jones:</b>\r\nAnytime I produce or work on mixing, I go back to the roots of the genre. In the realm of jersey club I am a huge fan of Mike Gip’s tracks; they sound super clean. With Juke and Footwork, I really appreciate Spinn, Rashad and RP Boo. The only song I remember hearing for the first time was a remix DJ PayPal did for DJ Bake, with Uniiqu3 on vocals; Booty Bounce Anthem I think it’s called. That’s how I learned about juke and jersey club.\r\nAlso really like Crystal Waters Gypsy Woman and anything that sounds similar to it.\r\n\r\nClassical Trax:\r\nI definitely think that shines through in your music; the Juke and Footwork tunes you’ve dropped recently definitely feel very connected to that sample heavy sound of Chicago; something that isn’t often found outside of the Chi.\r\nGypsy Woman is definitely an all-time classic. Speaking of which, if there was any piece of music; regardless of time and place, which you wish you could have produced yourself?\r\n\r\n<b>Kush Jones:</b>\r\nSo there were some compilations that used to be released via World Wide Juke and contained some of the hottest footwork tracks I’ve ever heard; joints from Traxman, DJ Tre, Jlin Juke Ellington, DJ Curt, etc.  Jlin had a track on one called “Guantanamo” that bangs. I think it was re released actually.\r\nI also wish I made beats for Keith Sweat. He had a lot of old school joints I like.\r\nClassical Trax:\r\nWhat would you say, is your proudest moment, so far, as a Producer or DJ?\r\n\r\n<b>Kush Jones:</b>\r\nIn the middle of Club Output, in Brooklyn, Lakim played my edit to Bok Bok’s Howard and the club got pretty lit. It was my first time at output too.\r\n\r\nClassical Trax:\r\nThat sounds crazy, speaking of clubs in New York City; how healthy is the scene where you are at the moment?\r\n\r\n<b>Kush Jones:</b>\r\nI love New York City and embrace the exclusivity of certain functions, however much of the time people get booked solely over Internet hype as opposed to people who make and play good music. I had a promoter who was originally from Kansas City tell me I can’t play in my own city; quite disgusting but you get in where you get in, where you fit in.\r\n\r\nClassical Trax:\r\nIt is good to have those exclusive events but it’s annoying when it comes at the cost of locals getting exposure. Is there anyone coming up (not just in New York) who you’d like to put a shine on? Who should we be checking next?\r\n\r\n<b>Kush Jones:</b>\r\nBassBear, El Blanco Nino, Swisha Sweet, Histo. 92’ Bulls.\r\n[There’s] A ton more I can name, but those are the cats I am watching and learning from.\r\n\r\nClassical Trax:\r\nIf music wasn’t your main outlet; where do you think you would be?\r\n\r\n<b>Kush Jones:</b>\r\nNot sure. I really like photography and telling stories so something in that realm or just playing the lotto everyday until I can cash out. I really don’t know.\r\n\r\nClassical Trax:\r\nWell it’s a good thing you’re doing what you do then!\r\n\r\n<b>Kush Jones:</b>\r\nYeah, my mind is generally in a million different places at once. Music is like the only thing that’ll keep me focused for extended time. That and listening to other people talk, I learn a lot just watching and listening.\r\n\r\nClassical Trax:\r\nFavourite Food?\r\n\r\n<b>Kush Jones:</b>\r\nWithout a doubt it’s oxtails, rice and peas, cabbage and some plantain on the side. I know you said favorite food but it’s inseparable as a dish. Can literally eat that for the rest of my life.\r\n\r\nClassical Trax:\r\nFavourite Drink?\r\n\r\n<b>Kush Jones:</b>\r\nModelo; however a buddy from Scotland gave the waviest review of Irn Bru and it may be my favorite drink just off of how highly he rated it. Never actually got to try it though.\r\n\r\nClassical Trax:\r\nHow did he describe it?\r\n\r\n<b>Kush Jones:</b>\r\nThe Ultimate Hangover drink. 1 can takes care of everything.\r\n\r\nClassical Trax:\r\nBest TV Show of all time?\r\n\r\n<b>Kush Jones:</b>\r\nChapelle Show\r\n\r\nClassical Trax:\r\nAnd finally, the best YouTube video of all time?\r\n\r\n<b>Kush Jones:</b>\r\nWhen I need motivation I always go back to this lol.. <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XHX4hWurt8M">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XHX4hWurt8M</a>\r\n\r\nCheck him out here\r\n\r\n<a href="https://soundcloud.com/kush_jones">https://soundcloud.com/kush_jones</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="https://twitter.com/ReallyKush">https://twitter.com/ReallyKush</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://instagram.com/reallykush">http://instagram.com/reallykush</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'CT Q&A #002-Kush Jones', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2015-09-22 18:32:37', '2015-09-22 17:32:37', '', 0, 'http://37.60.225.213/~class690/?p=88', 0, 'post', '', 0),
