(93, 1, '2015-09-22 18:35:05', '2015-09-22 17:35:05', '<b>Krizzli</b> is a swiss producer releasing stuff on labels like <a href="https://soundcloud.com/clubwerks/sets/cw004">Clubwerks</a>, or Files rec (which he runs) and this month on the Amy Becker TRX compilation. He went to the Red Bull Music Academy in Tokyo last year, and he learned a lot of things. He’s quite nice and we talked about his music, his perceptions or about his own label. Creaked x Files rec : Reboot is out now, so check this out because it is huge, features tracks from Akito, Galtier, Lemonick, Ansome, She’s Drunk and more …\r\n\r\n<a href="http://37.60.225.213/~class690/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/MHpfuJR.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-92" src="http://37.60.225.213/~class690/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/MHpfuJR-300x173.png" alt="MHpfuJR" width="300" height="173" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>How are you ? </b>\r\n\r\n<b>Krizzli</b> - Tip top, holidays !\r\n\r\n<b>How are you feelings your exams ?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>K</b> - Quite well I think, we’ll see\r\n\r\n<b>What do you study ?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>K</b> - i’m studying materials science and engineering in an engineering school here in switzerland\r\n\r\n<b>Intersting ! So, tell us more about the Red Bull Music academy, How was it ?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>K</b> - Amazing, incredible. It’s true what they say, it’s a life changing experience. I had the privilege to meet so many wonderful artists and I still have contact with a few participants. Music is a great way to meet new people\r\n\r\n<b>Did you meet artists who would interest you for collaborations? Lao or Mumdance for example ?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>K</b> - As much as I would have loved to collaborate with Mumdance, we didn’t end up having time to work together. Lao was in the other “term” and I didn’t meet him yet. But I’m totally open to collaboration in the future. At this point I’m mostly working on my personal sound and only started collaborating with my friend Lemonick. I’ll probably do more of this once I have time for myself. During the Academy, I pitched in with some groups to give input or just write a drum pattern and the likes, and I collaborated with Wife on a track. Also, I had a track with a French friend of mine, Felix, and Branko and Dre Skull, which was very cool.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<a href="https://soundcloud.com/redbullmusicacademy/felix-krizzli-branko-dre-skull">https://soundcloud.com/redbullmusicacademy/felix-krizzli-branko-dre-skull</a>\r\n\r\n<i><b>Felix, Krizzli, Branko &amp; Dre Skull - Omotesando</b></i>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<b>Ok, cool ! Let’s talk about your music, how do you describe it ?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>K</b> - Always hard to put labels on music these days, but I would say that my music is mostly UK-inspired. Some would say Bass, Grime. Some tracks on the other hand are inspired by Baltimore Club or Jersey Club. I also did (not so much anymore) some Techno on the Industrial side.\r\n\r\n<b>What do you prefer to play in club ?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>K</b> - It totally depends on the mood of the night, and the time of the set. I think it’s good to have various interests as a DJ and be able to shift away from one’s preferred style. So it would range from House and Techno, to Grime and Hip Hop, Bmore, UK Funky, Garage etc. If the crowd is receptive, what i love most is Bmore and Grime though, the energy is just crazy.\r\n\r\n<b>I’m agree with you about the energy ! Do you prepare your set or do you leave some serious place to the improvisation ?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>K</b> - No, I leave a lot of room for improv. My usb sticks are made so that it’s easy for me to scroll through and find the right tune at the right time. Gotta love tags in Rekordbox !\r\n\r\n<b>What’s your vision about the actual club scene ?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>K</b> - The perspective from here in Switzerland is kinda weird, and club scene is so global that I don’t really have an overview of it, but around here, Bass music is still kinda niche and it would be hard to satisfy a crowd that didn’t specifically come for this kind of sound. This results in a scene that feels very familiar. We all know each other between DJs that evolve in that national Bass Music scene no matter where we play (switzerland is tiny), a nice feeling of belonging. In general, I think the club scene gained a lot of interest over the past year or so, and I’m looking forward to the future!\r\n\r\n<b>Ok ! So, on what you bet for the future ? Do you have a dream about Switz club scene ?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>K</b> - I think that Grime will gain interest outside of the UK pretty soon. I wish that there were more clubs in Switzerland supporting that kind of “underground” music. Places really pushing forward these genres are scarce and often tiny.\r\n\r\n<b>It seems to be hard to make yourself a place in Switzerland, am I right ?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>K</b> - On one side, it is true that this makes it quite hard to find gigs, but on the other side, this also means that there is less “competition”. It’s really a balance of those 2 aspects. I’m glad there is no competition in this scene, almost all of the people i meet during my nocturnal excursions or musical endeavours end up being really good friends, it’s good for everyone, boosts creativity and helps with networking\r\n\r\n<b>How did you fall into UK bass ?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>K</b> - Soon after I started DJing, some friends and me decided to found a collective named Kartel Klub. Interacting with the other guys helped me broaden my musical horizon. At some point, I don’t really know specifically where and when, I noticed that what I was digging and playing was mostly coming from the UK. So i’d say it was by accident?\r\n\r\n<b>Ahah, well, and do you know what do you like in this music ?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>K</b> - It’s like asking why do you like bacon or grilled cheese sandwiches. It tastes good, it has fat, I love it, but I don’t really know why !\r\n\r\n<b>Ok ! And what are the artists who inspired you the most ?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>K</b> - On the UK side, guys like Boddika, Joy O, Paleman had a great influence on me at the beginning, all the swamp 81 crew really. I then fell in love with the likes of L-vis 1990, Bok Bok and the Night Slugs guys. Since a couple of years or so, Tessela and Mumdance also had a big impact on how my music sounds, I think. But this could not begin to cover all of the music that inspires me!\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<a href="https://soundcloud.com/cloudcreaked/sets/creaked-presents-files-rec-reboot">https://soundcloud.com/cloudcreaked/sets/creaked-presents-files-rec-reboot</a>\r\n\r\n<b><i>Creaked presents Files Rec : Re Boot</i></b>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<b>Yes, It’s complicated to find every influence… To finish our discussion, I’ve listened to the Creaked X Files rec compilation, that’s a really good job mate ! How can you describe this adventure ?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>K</b> - This compilation came as the perfect opportunity to officialize the partnering of Files Rec with another swiss imprint that I respect a lot : Creaked Records. They’ve been around for more than 10 years and they helped and will help me make something solid out of Files. It was also a way to re-start the label after a period of inactivity that was due to Files’ founder, Loïc Dupasquier, leaving the label in my hands so that he could focus on other projects. It also is an indication of what you can expect from the label sound-wise starting this fall. I’m really excited about what’s next!\r\n\r\n<b>What are the future project with Files Rec ?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>K</b> - The label will focus on digital releases, and I will be able to share the roster with Creaked for things like remixes and special side-projects.I’m really exited about the future releases !\r\n\r\n<b>Well, I will be patient and wait for new stuff ! Thank you.</b>\r\n\r\n<b>K</b> - Thank you so much ! Thanks for the opportunity !\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<i>Q &amp; A by Antoine Skavout\r\nVisual by Nigby Treinta</i>', 'CT Q&A #001 - KRIZZLI', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '91-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-09-22 18:35:05', '2015-09-22 17:35:05', '', 91, 'http://37.60.225.213/~class690/2015/09/22/91-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(94, 1, '2015-09-22 19:05:35', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'We are very excited to release our next interview in the series, featuring Pur Purr Purple and Ida Dillan of 3000 Textures!\r\n\r\n<a href="http://37.60.225.213/~class690/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/12053389_10156082597465273_885588781_n.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-96" src="http://37.60.225.213/~class690/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/12053389_10156082597465273_885588781_n-225x300.jpg" alt="12053389_10156082597465273_885588781_n" width="225" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\ninterview by Juliette Boos of Handle The Sound\r\n\r\n<a href="http://handlethesound.tumblr.com/">http://handlethesound.tumblr.com/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Hts</strong> : could you tell me a bit more about 3000 textures ?\r\n\r\nIDA : 3000 textures is a club concept hailing from Oslo, Norway, run by Ida Dillan and Purpurr Purple\r\n\r\nAnnette : We played a variety of trax from our favorite producers. 3000 texture is something like our platform of styles in music but also a channel where we can either be loud, fast, hard or bring lights to the things we like in music , art and culture\r\n\r\nIDA : and we can express ourselves how we want artistically, through music, fashion, digital art.. we like to provide club freedom and the feeling of being free and not judged in any shape or form\r\n\r\n<strong>Hts </strong>: that’s great. I like that way of thinking, not trying to git in some genres, just doing your things. So you’re not producing ?\r\n\r\nIDA : we do produce. I myself have made edits befire and i am releasing my first original track this fall.\r\n\r\n<strong>HTS </strong>: nice. Can’t wait to hear it.\r\n\r\nAnnette : thank you\r\n\r\n<strong>HTS</strong> : how would you define your sets ? and sounds ? like what artists influence you ?\r\n\r\nAnnette : we kinda have our own style but it fits in the club environments and the expression we share together. Our sound is 3000, forward bass music.\r\n\r\nIDA : we focus on high energy, and creating a certain vibe and feeling\r\nits difficult to "put it in a box" and our biggest influence is the intern\r\n<strong>HTS</strong> : yeah i see smile emoticon\r\nhow would you describe the music scene in Oslo? How''s your relationship with the Ball Em Up guys?\r\n\r\nAnnette : Its cute and nice. still. Although theres a lot of other scenes that dominates the whole club scene. We are friends with Ball Em up and Rytmeklubben guys too\r\n<strong>Hts</strong> : okay great!\r\nDo you think it''s harder for girls to find a place in this scene ? (not in Oslo, more like in general in the djing/producing « world » )\r\n\r\nAnnette : both yes and no. We dont like to focus so much on that girl ting. We know who we are and we do it the way we want to. I guess its all about taking your place and its possible. If we are thinking so much of what the guys are thinking we let it be a ting.. . But it is sad when guys get picked up faster because they got a potential, when girls gotta prove and "grow" big\r\n\r\nIda : i think "it is and it aint", sort of. it''s about the music, and finding your place in general, whether you''re a girl or a boy. i think it''s equally as hard, but it''s difficult to say because i''ve never experienced what it''s like for a guy\r\n\r\n<strong>Hts</strong> : yeah i agree\r\ni also feels like nowadays girls are too much showing that they''re "girls" producers/djs instead of producers/djs\r\nis there anyone you would love to collab with?\r\nAnnette : yes. So many. where do i start …\r\n\r\nIda : we''re always looking to collab and link up with like minded people, with the same focus and drive as us\r\nAnnette ; what ida says\r\n\r\nIda : the list is endless basically\r\n\r\n<strong>Hts </strong>: haha i see\r\nhave you ever been to france?\r\nfor la calypso?\r\nIda : yes Paris!! but not for la calypso unfortunately, i wanna make it a goal to go next year\r\n\r\nAnnette : Yes, i were there this year together with slick and Emil\r\nBut paris have wikked good DJs\r\n\r\n<strong>Hts</strong> : aww nice! Ida what have you done in Paris? What do you think of th emusic scene over there? and Annette how was La calypso? what was your favorite acts?\r\n\r\nIda : hehe i have only been visiting, so i''ve been eating those good hot dogs and going in the eiffel tower, basically\r\nnear killed myself on one of them hot dogs once because of that crazy mustard\r\ni swear there must be some sort of poison or something in there, i is strong as H***\r\ni''d love to go to a real vogue party in paris tho, that would be awesome\r\ni really like Dehousy too, he''s awesome\r\n\r\nannette : I saw Joke and Pearson Sound, Murlo,Teki ++. But my favorite set and the only set i wanted to catch was Betty. She''s such an amazing DJ and Club girl. I cant get over it..haha. She''s a warrior\r\nhts : what''s your upcoming projects as 3000 textures ?\r\nannette : we got plans to do more parties and tracks. and hopefully be able to work out an awesome compilation\r\n\r\n<strong>hts </strong>: nice. Thank you guys for your time.\r\n\r\n@3000textures\r\ntwitter.com/3oootextures\r\n<a class="mx-link" href="http://www.facebook.com/3000textures?_rdr" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">www.facebook.com/3000textures?_rdr</a>\r\n\r\n@purple_oslo\r\ntwitter.com/Purpurr\r\n<p class="">@idadillan\r\ntwitter.com/idadillan</p>', 'CT Q&A #005-3000 Textures', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2015-09-22 19:05:35', '2015-09-22 18:05:35', '', 0, 'http://37.60.225.213/~class690/?p=94', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(95, 1, '2015-09-22 18:49:21', '2015-09-22 17:49:21', 'We are very excited to release our next interview in the series, featuring Pur Purr Purple and Ida Dillan of 3000 Textures!\r\n\r\ninterview by Juliette Boos of Handle The Sound\r\n\r\n<a href="http://handlethesound.tumblr.com/">http://handlethesound.tumblr.com/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHts : could you tell me a bit more about 3000 textures ?\r\n\r\nIDA : 3000 textures is a club concept hailing from Oslo, Norway, run by Ida Dillan and Purpurr Purple\r\n\r\nAnnette : We played a variety of trax from our favorite producers. 3000 texture is something like our platform of styles in music but also a channel where we can either be loud, fast, hard or bring lights to the things we like in music , art and culture\r\n\r\nIDA : and we can express ourselves how we want artistically, through music, fashion, digital art.. we like to provide club freedom and the feeling of being free and not judged in any shape or form\r\n\r\nHts : that’s great. I like that way of thinking, not trying to git in some genres, just doing your things. So you’re not producing ?\r\n\r\nIDA : we do produce. I myself have made edits befire and i am releasing my first original track this fall.\r\n\r\nHTS : nice. Can’t wait to hear it.\r\n\r\nAnnette : thank you\r\n\r\nHTS : how would you define your sets ? and sounds ? like what artists influence you ?\r\n\r\nAnnette : we kinda have our own style but it fits in the club environments and the expression we share together. Our sound is 3000, forward bass music.\r\n\r\nIDA : we focus on high energy, and creating a certain vibe and feeling\r\nits difficult to "put it in a box" and our biggest influence is the intern\r\nHTS : yeah i see smile emoticon\r\nhow would you describe the music scene in Oslo? How''s your relationship with the Ball Em Up guys?\r\n\r\nAnnette : Its cute and nice. still. Although theres a lot of other scenes that dominates the whole club scene. We are friends with Ball Em up and Rytmeklubben guys too\r\nHts : okay great!\r\nDo you think it''s harder for girls to find a place in this scene ? (not in Oslo, more like in general in the djing/producing « world » )\r\n\r\nAnnette : both yes and no. We dont like to focus so much on that girl ting. We know who we are and we do it the way we want to. I guess its all about taking your place and its possible. If we are thinking so much of what the guys are thinking we let it be a ting.. . But it is sad when guys get picked up faster because they got a potential, when girls gotta prove and "grow" big\r\n\r\nIda : i think "it is and it aint", sort of. it''s about the music, and finding your place in general, whether you''re a girl or a boy. i think it''s equally as hard, but it''s difficult to say because i''ve never experienced what it''s like for a guy\r\n\r\nHts : yeah i agree\r\ni also feels like nowadays girls are too much showing that they''re "girls" producers/djs instead of producers/djs\r\nis there anyone you would love to collab with?\r\nAnnette : yes. So many. where do i start …\r\n\r\nIda : we''re always looking to collab and link up with like minded people, with the same focus and drive as us\r\nAnnette ; what ida says\r\n\r\nIda : the list is endless basically\r\n\r\nHts : haha i see\r\nhave you ever been to france?\r\nfor la calypso?\r\nIda : yes Paris!! but not for la calypso unfortunately, i wanna make it a goal to go next year\r\n\r\nAnnette : Yes, i were there this year together with slick and Emil\r\nBut paris have wikked good DJs\r\n\r\nHts : aww nice! Ida what have you done in Paris? What do you think of th emusic scene over there? and Annette how was La calypso? what was your favorite acts?\r\n\r\nIda : hehe i have only been visiting, so i''ve been eating those good hot dogs and going in the eiffel tower, basically\r\nnear killed myself on one of them hot dogs once because of that crazy mustard\r\ni swear there must be some sort of poison or something in there, i is strong as H***\r\ni